Here is the code of completed_callback:
```c
static void
completed_callback (void *cls,
                    struct MHD_Connection *connection,
                    void **req_cls,
                    enum MHD_RequestTerminationCode toe)
{
  struct timeval *tv = *req_cls;
  struct timeval tve;
  uint64_t delta;
  (void) cls;         /* Unused. Silent compiler warning. */
  (void) connection;  /* Unused. Silent compiler warning. */
  (void) toe;         /* Unused. Silent compiler warning. */

  if (NULL == tv)
    return;
  gettimeofday (&tve, NULL);

  delta = ((uint64_t) (tve.tv_sec - tv->tv_sec)) * 1000000LL
          + (uint64_t) tve.tv_usec - (uint64_t) tv->tv_usec;
  if (delta < SMALL)
    small_deltas[delta]++;
  else
    fprintf (stdout, "D: %" PRIu64 " 1\n", delta);
  free (tv);
}
```

explanation: The provided code fragment contains no calls to memcmp, strcmp, strncmp, or other functions that perform string comparisons. All operations are time calculations, conditional checks on numeric delta, I/O (fprintf), and memory deallocation (free). Therefore there are no occurrences in this fragment that could violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14 (which forbids using memcmp to compare null-terminated strings). No other lines perform string comparisons or use memcmp, so nothing here needs further investigation for that specific rule.
